#!N  #!Rtall870 Tracking the Image window with another window #!N #!N 
#!N If you want to have two images visible, and want 
to alternatively control the viewpoint, resolution, etc. of one of the 
windows while having the second window display a different object from 
the same viewpoint, simply use the  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   camera #!EF output of 
the Image tool as input to the  #!F-adobe-times-bold-r-normal--18*   camera #!EF input 
of a Display tool. The first input of Display should be 
the other object you wish to view. For an example, see 
WindVorticity.net. #!N #!N For more information on using the Image tool 
in the user interface, see  #!Luseimag,dxall299 h Using the Image Window  #!EL  in IBM Visualization Data Explorer 
User's Guide. Also see  #!Ldisplay,dxall807 h Display  #!EL  for information under the following headings: 
#!N  #!Lhardsof,dxall825 h Differences between Hardware and Software Rendering  #!EL  ,  #!Lhardren,dxall824 h Rendering Approximations  #!EL  ,  #!Ludfcmps,dxall814 h Using Default Color Maps  #!EL  ,  #!Ludcmps,dxall813 h Using Direct Color Maps  #!EL  ,  #!Lchrndpr,dxall819 h Changing Rendering Properties  #!EL  , 
 #!Lgammaco,dxall815 h Gamma Correction  #!EL  ,  #!Limgcach,dxall818 h Image Caching  #!EL  ,  #!Ltextmap,dxall826 h Texture Mapping  #!EL  See also  #!Lcolor,dxall792 h Color  #!EL  for information on 
 #!Lcvolrnd,dxall820 h Coloring Objects for Volume Rendering  #!EL  . #!N #!N Example Visual Programs #!N #!N Nearly every 
example visual program uses the Image tool. ImageTool.net uses the hidden-by-default 
parameters. Image_wo_UI.net demonstrates a substitute Image macro using SuperviseWindow, SuperviseState, and 
Display, which can be used independent of the User Interface. #!N 
